 Only trapped particles can contribute in this case.
 At large aspect ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{{\rm min}}\approx B_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, so most of their kinetic energy lies in the magnetic moment,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{mv^{2}}{2} & \approx\mu B_{0}(\tht).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We consider a magnetic perturbation mode
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
H_{n} & =\left\langle \left(mv_{\parallel}^{2}+J_{\perp}\omega_{c}\right)\frac{B_{n}(\tht)}{B_{0}(\tht)}e^{inq\tht}\right\rangle _{b}\\
 & \approx\frac{mv^{2}}{2B_{a}}\left\langle B_{n}(\vartheta)e^{inq\tht}\right\rangle _{b}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Shaing2009-35009 assumes a perturbation of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
B_{n}(\tht) & =-B_{a}\varepsilon_{n}(\tht)e^{in\ph_{0}}=-B_{a}\varepsilon_{n}(\tht)e^{in(q\tht-\ph)}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

